    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>In isomeric amines, the order of boiling points follows the order:</p>\n<p>$1^{\\circ}$ amine $>2^{\\circ}$ amine $>3^{\\circ}$ amine. Amongst given $1^{\\circ}$ amines: $n-\\mathrm{C}_4 \\mathrm{H}_9 \\mathrm{NH}_2$ has higher boiling point than $\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{NH}_2$ because boiling point decreases with branching.</p>\n<p>$$ \\begin{array}{|c|c|c|} \\hline \\text { Compound } & \\text { Molar mass } & \\text { B.P. (K) } \\\\ \\hline \\text { n- } \\mathrm{C}_4 \\mathrm{H}_9 \\mathrm{NH}_2\\left(1^{\\circ}\\right) & 73 & 350.8 \\\\ \\hline\\left(\\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5\\right)_2 \\mathrm{NH}^{\\circ}\\left(2^{\\circ}\\right) & 73 & 329.3 \\\\ \\hline \\mathrm{C}_2 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{~N}\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_2\\left(3^{\\circ}\\right) & 73 & 310.5 \\\\ \\hline\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3 \\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{NH}_2\\left(1^{\\circ}\\right) & 73 & 318.15 \\\\ \\hline \\end{array} $$</p>",
